{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488618","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488618"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:49:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:49:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"493"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"493","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/493"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.27,0.57,0.09,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"493"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42649"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"493","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/493"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"493"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27589"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"423"},{"type":"tags","id":"1184"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2808"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3076"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10820"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10939"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42649","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/42649"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two day history of flashing lights and six hour visual loss. He has not had any recent eye trauma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe has a medical history of type 2 diabetes mellitus and hypertension. His medications include metformin, semaglutide and perindopril.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination he appears well. His pulse rate is 72bpm and blood pressure is 165/95mmHg. Visual acuity is at 6/6 in the right eye and at counting fingers in the left eye. Fundoscopic examination of the left eye is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Diabetic retinopathy","Posterior vitreous detachment","Retinal detachment","Vitreous haemorrhage","Intraocular inflammation"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe fundus shows smooth serous elevation of the retina consistent with an inferior \u003Cstrong\u003Eretinal detachment, \u003C/strong\u003Eand also partly involves the macula\u003Cstrong\u003E.\u003C/strong\u003E This is an ophthalmological emergency and requires urgent ophthalmology referral for surgery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiabetic retinopathy \u003C/strong\u003Eis a risk factor for retinal detachment. The fundus of non-proliferative retinopathy would demonstrate the presence of exudate, haemorrhage and ischaemic events (cotton wool spots). In proliferative diabetic retinopathy, angiogenesis occurs which can contribute to retinal detachment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPosterior vitreous detachment (PVD) \u003C/strong\u003Eoccurs when the vitreous gel pulls away which can result in damage to the retina, and as a result is also a risk factor of retinal detachment. PVD can also present with flashes, but does not demonstrate the characteristic smooth serous elevation as seen in the fundoscopy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVitreous haemorrhage\u003C/strong\u003E can also present with painless vision loss and can occur secondary to proliferative diabetic retinopathy, posterior vitreous detachment or retinal tear. This is not seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntraocular inflammation \u003C/strong\u003Einvolves inflammation of the anterior eye such as the iris and ciliary body. It typically presents as a sudden painful red eye which is not present within this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Retinal detachment is a medical emergency presenting with painless vision loss and flashing lights."],"references":["Bowling, B. (2015). Kanski\u2019s clinical ophthalmology (8th ed.). W B Saunders"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27589"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"493"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20519"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20519","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20519"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/CAEaXxRNQH7qCssULFHpTB99avP7CV.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/CAEaXxRNQH7qCssULFHpTB99avP7CV.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":552,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27589","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/27589"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-02-14T20:44:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-02-14T20:44:49+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"493"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42649"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{